 into the unity and purpose of history, a reflection on human nature and the place of humans in the cosmic order, an examination of what was beginning to be called “culture,” and a narrative of cultural progress across time among different peoples. Along the way, Herder considers a dizzying variety of topics, including the formation of the earth and solar system, species change, race, the immortality of the soul, the establishment of society, and the pursuit of happiness. Above all, the Ideas is an anthropology—what Alexander Pope had termed an “essay on man”—pervaded by an appropriately humane spirit.A fresh and much-needed modern translation of the complete Ideas, this volume reintroduces English readers to a classic of Enlightenment thought.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHistoryxPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Individual Philosophers.2bisacsh  aEnlightenment.  aEurope.  aGerman literature.  aGerman philosophy.  aGermany.  aGregory Moore.  aIdeas for the Philosophy of the History of Mankind.  aJohann Gottfried Herder.  aPhilosophy of history.  aanthropology.  acultural history.  afate.  ahistory of mankind.  ahumanity.  amankind.  amodernity.  aphilosophy.  aprinceton university press.  aworld history.1 aMoore, Gregory Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311074975540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691255705?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691255705423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780691255705/original  a978-3-11-074975-5  Princeton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles